# HDH Writing Style — Voice, Tone, and Conventions

These rules apply to all documentation in the `docs/` directory. Follow them when writing new pages or rewriting existing ones.

---

## Voice and tone

Write in a casual, conversational tone. Keep sentences short and in the present tense.

Speak **to** the developer, not **at** them. Use "you", not "the user" or "users".

- ❌ The user can run Docker-in-Docker in a Background step.
- ✅ You can run Docker-in-Docker in a Background step.

Do **not** use "please". Be authoritative but approachable.

- ❌ Please try running the pipeline again.
- ✅ Run the pipeline again.

Write in **present tense**, **active voice**.

- ❌ You will need to install a delegate in your Kubernetes cluster.
- ✅ Install a delegate in your Kubernetes cluster.
- ❌ The delegate will be added to the Delegates list.
- ✅ The delegate is added to the Delegates list.

---

## Link phrasing — "Go to X to do Y"

Always use **"Go to [link] to [verb phrase]"**. Never use "see", "refer to", "to learn more about", "to find out more", or "for more information".

- ❌ See [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) for the permissions hierarchy.
- ❌ Refer to the [permissions reference](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference) for details.
- ❌ To learn more about delegates, see the [delegate documentation](/docs/platform/delegates/get-started/overview).
- ✅ Go to [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) to understand the permissions hierarchy.
- ✅ Go to the [permissions reference](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference) to review required permissions.
- ✅ Go to [delegate overview](/docs/platform/delegates/get-started/overview) to install and configure a delegate.

Use meaningful link text. Never write `[here](url)`, `[this doc](url)`, or `[click here](url)`.

- ❌ Go to [here](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) for details.
- ✅ Go to [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) to manage permissions.

---

## Buttons and exact UI labels

When you refer to the **exact** text of a control in the Harness UI (button, menu command, account setting name, failure strategy option, or similar), wrap that string in **single straight quotes**: `'Mark as Failed'`, `'Save'`, `'Allow users to mark a running Step as failure'`.

Use quotes for the literal label the user sees. Do not use quotes for generic references (for example "the execution details page" or "your pipeline").

In steps, write `Select 'Mark as Failed'.` when the reader must click that control, not bold alone.

---

## Prerequisites section

The **Prerequisites** section lists what a user needs before following the page's instructions. Keep it scannable and not text-heavy.

**Formatting rules:**
- Each prerequisite should be a short bullet starting with a bold label, followed by a brief description and a link where relevant.
- The bold label itself should be concise (2–4 words). Don't bold entire sentences.
- Avoid nesting explanatory paragraphs inside prerequisite bullets — if more detail is needed, link to it.
- Each prerequisite that has a dedicated doc page should link to that page using "Go to [link] to …" phrasing.

**Example:**

❌ Too text-heavy and over-bolded:
```
- **Harness project access:** You need permission to open the failing pipeline execution and view logs. At minimum, **View** on [Pipelines](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference#pipelines) is required; **Execute** is needed if you will re-run the pipeline to verify a fix. An administrator assigns these via [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) and [Manage roles](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/add-manage-roles).
```

✅ Concise and scannable:
```
- **Harness project access:** View or Execute permissions on the pipeline. Go to [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) to configure roles.
- **Connector access:** Access on any connector the pipeline uses at runtime. Go to the [permissions reference](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference#shared-resources) for details.
```

**What belongs in Prerequisites vs. the body:**
- Prerequisites = things the user must have or know **before starting**.
- Detailed configuration steps or nuanced permission logic belong in the body of the page, not in the Prerequisites list.

---

## No em dashes

Do not use em dashes (`—`) anywhere in documentation. They read as informal or rushed and make sentences harder to scan.

Instead, rewrite the sentence, use a comma, or use a semicolon.

- ❌ The connector must be configured — otherwise the pipeline will fail.
- ✅ Configure the connector before running the pipeline.
- ✅ The connector must be configured; otherwise, the pipeline fails.

- ❌ Harness RBAC — which controls who can do what — is configured at account, org, or project scope.
- ✅ Harness RBAC controls who can do what. Configure it at account, org, or project scope.

---

## Lists

Start each list with an introductory sentence. Do not start a list directly after a heading with no prose between them (unless the heading is itself a clear enough introduction).

Use **bold labels followed by a colon** when items have a label and description:
```
- **Label:** Description.
```

Don't bold entire sentences or descriptions — only the label word(s).

Use Oxford commas in inline lists:
- ❌ You need a Harness account, a GitHub account and an IDE.
- ✅ You need a Harness account, a GitHub account, and an IDE.

---

## No gerunds

Do not use gerunds (–ing verb forms) anywhere in documentation: headings, body text, button labels, or link text.

Use the base imperative form instead.

| ❌ Avoid | ✅ Use |
|---|---|
| Installing the delegate | Install the delegate |
| Configuring your pipeline | Configure your pipeline |
| Running the script | Run the script |
| Adding a connector | Add a connector |
| Troubleshooting errors | Troubleshoot errors |

This applies in all contexts — headings, numbered steps, bulleted lists, and inline prose.

- ❌ Start by installing the delegate and then configuring your environment.
- ✅ Install the delegate, then configure your environment.

Exceptions: noun-phrase section titles where a gerund is the natural name of a concept, such as **Troubleshooting** (as a section header) or **Prerequisites**.

---

## Headings

Use sentence case: capitalize the first word and proper nouns only.

Use imperative verb phrases, not gerunds (see **No gerunds** above):
- ❌ Installing the delegate
- ✅ Install the delegate

Don't include "Step N:", "How to", "Introduction to", or "Review:" in headings.

Don't start the page body with a heading (like `## Introduction`). Write an intro paragraph first.

---

## Admonitions

Use `:::tip` for small helpful hints that are not required reading.
Use `:::warning` sparingly — only when something bad could happen if the user ignores it.
Use `:::info My Title` for useful guidance that needs to stand out. Always give it a short, descriptive title instead of the default "Information".
Do **not** use `:::note` (poor visual contrast; use `:::info` instead).

Give admonitions a short, lowercase title that describes the content:
- ❌ `:::tip account level access`
- ✅ `:::tip Check account-level flags`
